to a general portrait of Canadian city politics. Warren Magnusson's introductory essay is itself a sketch for such a portrait. Especially designed for readers who are new to the subject, this essay reviews the development of local government and politics in Canada as a whole. It explains those features of municipal politics that the authors of the case studies have had to take for granted, and it sets the context for comparative analysis. Such analysis is Andrew Sancton's concern in his concluding essay. He bases his observations on the studies in this book, and pays particular attention to the way in which the pattern revealed differs from the American and the British. As he says, Canadian city politics is almost exclusively about boosterism, land development, and the enhancement of property. This is its unifying and distinguishing feature -- a feature that is clarified by the analyses in each chapter of City Politics in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMunicipal governmentzCanadavCase studies. 7aLAW / Government / State, Provincial & Municipal.2bisacsh1 aAndrew, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAucoin, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutstein, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiernan, Matthew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightbody, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagnusson, Warren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagnusson, Warren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSancton, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct